⚖️ LCES: Legal Calculus Educational System

🟦 AI Hallucination and Controlled Legal Workflow

AI in legal work can hallucinate.

It can invent:

- 📚 Cases

• 🧾 Citations

• 📌 Facts

• ⏰ Deadlines

• ⚠️ Rules

• ✅ False confidence

That risk is real.

LCES does not pretend otherwise.

🟨 LCES is designed around AI’s limits

The goal is not to let AI “be the lawyer.”

The goal is controlled use.

LCES separates the workflow into defined roles:

- 🧩 Architect — structures the issue

• ✍️ Builder — drafts from the structure

• 🛡️ Inspector — stress-tests the output

• 👤 Human — verifies and decides

🔹 LCES requires discipline

Before work proceeds, the system requires:

- SCU structure

• Record-first inputs

• Clear issue framing

• Concrete factual anchors

• Defined objectives

• Verification of every citation and claim

🛡️ The core safeguard:

AI may organize.

AI may draft.

AI may expose weaknesses.

But the human must verify.

The human must judge.

The human must remain responsible.

⚖️ LCES does not rely on blind trust in AI.

It uses constrained workflow to reduce drift, preserve the record, and keep humans in control.

That is a safer model than pretending hallucinations do not exist.

